This is a bug in dot's xdot backend.  xdot files are supposed to be valid dot files, but dot is not preserving the double backslash characters properly when writing the xdot:

    $ dot -Txdot quotes.dot 
    digraph g {
    	graph [_draw_="c 9 -#fffffe00 C 7 -#ffffff P 4 0 0 0 36 71.49 36 71.49 0 ",
    		bb="0,0,71.494,36",
    		xdotversion=1.7
    	];
    	node [label="\N"];
    	n0	 [_draw_="c 7 -#000000 e 35.75 18 36 18 ",
    		_ldraw_="F 14 11 -Times-Roman c 7 -#000000 T 35.75 14.3 0 39 8 -\\"test\\" ",
    		height=0.5,
    		label="\\\"test\\\"",
    		pos="35.747,18",
    		width=0.99297];
    }

Dot itself can't parse its own xdot.

And the exact same thing happens with HTML labels:

    $ cat escapes.dot 
    digraph {
        c [label = "\\\""];
        html [label = <\">];
    }
    $ xdot.py ^C
    $ dot -Txdot escapes.dot | dot -Tpng > /dev/null
    Error: <stdin>: syntax error in line 8 near '\'

So there's no workaround.

There's nothing I can do about this on xdot.py.  In short, this must be fixed on dot's xdot backend itself.

