I think you'd have to rewrite it. Autograd works on functions by boxing arguments before they get passed in. Here, the argument you care about boxing isn't actually an argument of `output`, but rather it's an argument of `np.dot`. So in this simple example, it's really the gradient of `np.dot` that you want, with respect to its first argument, rather than any gradient of `output`.

You might be able to reorganize your code so that inside a class method you call a pure function with arguments that are class members, like this:

```python
class A(object):
    def __init__(self):
        self.W = np.random.rand(size=(10,10))

    def output(self, x):
        return self._output(self.W, x)
```

Then you can call `grad` on the `_output` method to get its gradient with respect to argument 0.

Just so we're clear what you mean, can you confirm this is the issue?

In each hook, all the handlers whose preconditions are true will run again, even if they ran in a previous hook. So as long as `random_flag` is set, `setup_stuff` will run in _every_ hook. This also means the `update-status` hook which runs **every 5 minutes**.

I don't know the context, but the right solution here is probably

```python
@when ('config.changed.foo')
def changed_config():
  setup_stuff()

@when('random_flag')
@when_not('mycharm.setup')
def setup_stuff()
    # do stuff...
    set_flag('mycharm.setup')
```

In this case, `setup_stuff` will run one time when `random_flag` is set, and will run again each time `foo` changes.

Are you asking us to make it more clear that a hook will re-run if its preconditions are true, even if it already ran in a previous hook?

